Text: An SPCA officer rescued this kitten from a shopping mall’s loading bay! Her limbs were stuck in a drain and were covered with sticky glue, possibly from a pest control company’s rodent glue trap that was found beside the drain. Luckily, a security guard called us for help. At SPCA, our veterinary team removed the glue and our inspectors reported the incident to AVS.  Glue board traps have caused multiple accidents in the past and not all animals are lucky enough to survive. We have previously appealed for a ban of glue board traps due to the suffering caused to ALL animals that are trapped on them. #spcasgrescues #spcasgclinic #spcasingapore

WOUNDED CAT’S AMAZING RECOVERY [GRAPHIC] Godfather was rescued with a severe necrotic wound, which exposed his tail bone. He was found extremely dehydrated and emaciated and his tail was severely damaged by a bacterial infection. . Our #spcasgclinic veterinary team started work on him immediately, including administering fluid therapy and performing a blood test. Test results revealed he was anaemic and had Feline Leukemia Virus (FeLV). We put him on an extensive course of antibiotics, flushed and cleaned his wound twice daily, and showered him with tender loving care. . A week into treatment, Godfather showed amazing progress. His red blood count had doubled and his open wound contracted to half its original size.  Once his anaemic condition was resolved, our vet performed surgery to amputate his tail bone. While recovering, he gained weight and his wound healed completely. After five months of care at SPCA, he was adopted into a loving family. <U+0001F499> #spcasgclinic #spcasingapore

Reposted by @spcasingapore APPEAL FOR INFORMATION: HORRIFIC ABUSE OF PUPPY  A video has been circulating on WhatsApp, featuring a woman (in screenshot) horrifically abusing a puppy by burning its eyes and breaking its limbs while its mouth is tied shut.  There are indications that the incident may not have occurred in Singapore but we are exploring all possibilities and urgently appealing for credible information to seek justice for the puppy.  If you know the identity and whereabouts of the woman, please provide the information to the relevant agency in your country. Alternatively, you can contact us at inspector@spca.org.sg and we will relay the message in strict confidence.  Let us stand united against animal cruelty, wherever it may occur.  NOTE: Please do not circulate the video. There are syndicates that profit from animal torture films, including some that are produced for sexual fetish. #spcasingapore

SPCA VOLUNTEER SPOTLIGHT — “I work from 6am to 6pm on weekdays as a gold trader but no amount of money can compare to the immense joy I feel when volunteering at SPCA. For a long time, I followed the good work SPCA did for community animals in Singapore. So when I decided it was time for me to start giving back more actively, SPCA was my number one choice.  My life value is compassion. Every day, I try to incorporate that into everything I do. So when it comes to caring for these animals, it’s easy to be committed. A couple of weeks after my first volunteer session, the shelter dogs finally recognised me and I was no longer just a stranger. It was such a warm feeling. They started to be comfortable around me and I became even more comfortable being with them. The memories I made with these amazing animals is something I will take to my grave.” - Prem, 34, Shelter Helper, with Harvey  Dedicated volunteers like Prem keep our services running. To find out ways you can help us, view our IG highlights (‘help us’) to find out more. <U+0001F499> #spcasgstories #spcasingapore

At around 12.15am, @spcasingapore alerted me to a case of a cat seemingly on a collar and an attached leash on an overhead bridge in a cluster beside my feeding area. I had scheduled a trapping session tonight, at that same location, at 1am, and a ginger white cat was one of my targets. I thought this cat on the overhead bridge is my targeted TNR cat. So The Husband and I went over, to help SPCA watch over the cat (in case it falls off the bridge) and also to ascertain if it is my targeted cat.  To our horror, the cat was already half-body out of the mini platform, and may fall onto the busy road below the bridge anytime. Thankfully SPCA arrived soon, because I almost died of panic watching over the cat. I couldn't tell if it is my targeted cat because the cat was entirely camouflaged by the plants.  When Mark of SPCA arrived, we did a quick assessment. There was no way to get to the cat safely. Mark risked the danger of himself falling over, and climbed over to get to the cat. (Thank you so much! I owe you more coffee!) Cat was brought to safety, and Mark suffered some scratches. Then I realized this cat has a tipped ear, and is not my targeted TNR cat.  Which can only mean it is a lost cat.  SPCA has taken in this cat to locate its owner. I will follow up with this case should the owner is not found.  Cat was found in Sengkang, Rivervale Crescent. The ginger-white cat is suspected a male, big and fat, has untrimmed nails, and was on a red slip leash meant for dogs. I will only be able to find out if the cat has a microchip tomorrow.  So, whoever who has any information about this cat, please DM me. This skinny, male, unsterilized ginger cat was found at Beng's block, right where Beng always naps at.  Hungry fellow devoured 3 tins of wet food in one go. Then I noticed blood on the feeding paper. Took a closer look at him and realized... (1) All his whiskers have been cut very short. (2) He has a big, rotting abscess on his lower lip.  I then decided to do a more thorough visual check. There are some other cuts around his mouth. Ginger chap is a young adult, probably 1 - 2 years old. Very tame and docile. His nails have been trimmed extremely short, way shorter than what I would do for cats. His paws are very dirty, so it is likely he has been outdoors for at least 2 days already.  I have lodged a case with @spcasingapore on suspected abuse and abandonment. SPCA have taken him in for treatment. I will follow up with another report to AVS and SPF.  Look, I don't care who taught you to cut short your cat's whiskers so your cat will not be able to find its way home after you abandon it. Because I can tell you now, this DOES NOT work. I also cannot confirm if his injury happened before or after you abandoned him, but good luck to you. You conveniently abandoned a cat who clearly would not survive outdoors. Like, hello? No whiskers, no long nails, doesn't know how to hunt for food... So how to defend itself against danger? The cat will not be able to climb trees at all, excuse me? #InsertExpletivesHere . #SPCAsg #SPCASingapore #CatRescue #AdoptionSavesLives #catwelfaresociety #sgcats #catsofsingapore #singaporecats #sgpets #catsg #cotwsg #catsofsg #clubpetsmag #petsmagazinesg #hdbcats #singaporepets #supportadoptionsg #TheDodo #TheAnimalRescueSite #catloverssingapore #catsofigsg #sgig #sgcat #sengkangcats

Auto check-ins (i.e. voluntarily offered eye contact) is such a great skill for communication and engagement with your dog. It can help with cueing the next behaviour, redirecting your dog away from a trigger, change directions, loose leash walking... etc. My Humans reinforce me as much as they can whenever I check in so that I will do it more often. We do this both on leash and off leash, because being off leash doesn’t mean it’s time for the human to just do their own thing, go on their phones, or just let dogs play with each other rampantly. It’s a time for a dog to move more freely but still be engaged with their handler! My Humans find that I actually check in more when I’m off leash because they’re even more conscious about rewarding me for check-ins when I’m off leash because it’s such an important behaviour! We also do this both on my left and right side so that I’m not always stretching my head and looking up on one side as that can be uncomfortable after too long.  Human’s tshirt is from @woofcultr. So this late afternoon, a resident in my cluster alerted me about a cat who was loitering around the corridor on level 5 since yesterday morning. And then the residents started to panic when the cat jumped into one of the resident's air-conditioning compressor ledge.  I went over to assess the situation. It was too risky for me to do the rescue alone.  This cat is one of the 5 newly abandoned cats found in my feeding areas. He has not fully trusted me yet. I still have to keep a wide distance from him before he would eat. So if I try to get him out of the compressor ledge alone, there would be a high chance he would simply just jump off the ledge and plummet down 5 storeys. Too unsafe.  Thankfully, Mohan and Mark from @spcasingapore came down swiftly and helped to get this boy out of the ledge. (I owe you guys coffee!) SPCA would help to sterilize this boy as a TNR case.  I also got to thank the residents for their understanding and letting us into their houses to assess the situation and carry out the rescue.  Honestly, I am dead tired of all these nonsensical abandonment. And as I am typing this post, another case comes in. How to keep up? Gather round the tree stump children and let me tell you a story about a dog named Dave (from my Human’s perspective): .  Dave was found when he was about 2 years old by @spcasingapore and no one had come to claim him. I don’t know if he was a stray or not. So he waited and waited in the SPCA... at one point, he even got heartworm and had to be put in isolation for months! <U+0001F628> It was a rough time. He was generally known for spinning in his kennel and growling and slamming himself against his kennel door when other dogs walked past. He even caused damage to one door once and had to move to another kennel. <U+0001F629> During public visiting hours, he either just slept or barked at them, so he didn’t seem particularly friendly.  I started volunteering at the SPCA in 2016 and that’s when I met Dave! I became a dog mentor under the guidance of the amazing @cheerfuldogs and he was the first dog I just knew I wanted as a mentee. It took a bit of time for us to bond as Dave takes time to warm up to people, but we did eventually through our walks, training, and enrichment games! I looked forward to all my weekends with him. I learnt to work with his dog reactivity, muzzle training, crate training, play nose work games... etc. And all of this also led me to want to get on this dog training path!  A month before leaving for the UK, I made the crazy decision to take him with me. It was really rushed but with the help of @theflyingfido on paperwork & transport, @cheerfuldogs’s guidance on crate training him for the flight, and @theawesome_pup and @hapshapshappy helping to take him to the airport for me, it all worked out in the end!  I adopted Dave because I love him, because he waited so so long for a home and desperately deserves one, and because in a practical way, he’s a dog I knew I could manage and would fit in with our life. He’s helped me so much with my assessments and my training skills, he’s made my relationship with my partner stronger, he’s enriched my life, and he teaches me so much everyday. Love this boi. <U+2764><U+FE0F>

Now that Human is back volunteering at @spcasingapore, she’s reminded of the crazy time where she had to go to the shelter a number of times a week to crate train me for the flight! Good thing Human did some crate training with me before deciding to adopt me to the UK, so we weren’t starting from scratch to go in a month’s time. .  Through this training process where I was NOT being lured or forced into the crate, I learnt to go in willingly and was rewarded for doing so. (Swipe to see me getting in the crate and chilling in there for a little while!) This helped me build a bit of resilience, as when the day came for me to go to the airport with @theawesome_pup’s mentor and @hapshapshappy’s human, I had to be let out of the crate midway because I vomited in it while in the van. I kinda wasn’t keen on going back in after that, but since the training process didn’t involve luring me into something potentially aversive like that crate before, @theawesome_pup and @hapshapshappy were able to throw a few pieces of duck liver to get me in again that one time since treats were not “poisoned” for me. <U+0001F64C>  We were also really grateful for the generous help and advice from @cheerfuldogs during this process! <U+263A><U+FE0F><U+2764><U+FE0F> Would have been so lost without them!  #forcefree #dog #singaporedogs #spcasingapore #sonya6000 #adoptdontshop #mongrel #positivereinforcement #dogsofsingapore #mongrelsofinstagram #dogstagram #singapawrean #singaporespecial #rescuedog #rescuedogsofinstagram #shelterdog #shelterdogsofinstagram  #dogsofliverpool #dogsofengland #dogsofbritain #liverpooldogs #liverpoolpets

I’m now getting more wonderful opportunities to be off leash in safe quiet places! At the same time, we’re continuing to work on my recall! (Swipe to see how fast I go. In the first video, I came over with just my name when my recall cue is really “come here” <U+0001F61D>) .  The important thing is that I am always rewarded with nice treats for recalling and being called doesn’t always mean I have to get back on the leash! Often times our recall just means TREAT TIME and go back to whatever I was doing before.  There is no need for any shock collar, e-collar, threats, stim, whatever... Thoughts today: <U+0001D682><U+0001D698><U+0001D696><U+0001D68E><U+0001D69D><U+0001D692><U+0001D696><U+0001D68E><U+0001D69C> <U+0001D690><U+0001D698><U+0001D698><U+0001D68D> <U+0001D692><U+0001D697><U+0001D69D><U+0001D68E><U+0001D697><U+0001D69D><U+0001D692><U+0001D698><U+0001D697><U+0001D69C> <U+0001D68A><U+0001D695><U+0001D698><U+0001D697><U+0001D68E> <U+0001D68A><U+0001D69B><U+0001D68E><U+0001D697>’<U+0001D69D> <U+0001D68E><U+0001D697><U+0001D698><U+0001D69E><U+0001D690><U+0001D691>.  Having the good intention of wanting a better behaved dog that fits in better at home and in society but using aversive methods and tools or sending him/her to an aversive trainer (whether they’re popular/famous or not) compromises a dog’s physical, emotional, and mental well-being .  Having the good intention of wanting all dogs saved but subjecting some to a lifetime of behaviour suppression, fear, learned helplessness, and pain greatly diminishes their quality of life. Is such a life even worth living?  Having the good intention of getting a worried dog in the situation or environment it’s worried about by luring them in or by just forcing them to “face their fears” can lead to emotional conflict, makes their worries worse, or cause them to shut down.  When we know better, we do better. And to know better we have to keep learning and educating ourselves.  #sonya6000 #dogsofsingapore #forcefreetraining #forcefree #dog #dogs #singaporedogs #spcasingapore #adoptdontshop #mongrel #positivereinforcement #mongrelsofinstagram #dogstagram #singapawrean #singaporespecial #rescuedog #rescuedogsofinstagram #shelterdog #shelterdogsofinstagram  #dogsofliverpool #dogsofengland #dogsofbritain #liverpooldogs #liverpoolpets

Never feel put down by people who try to call you a “cookie pusher” for using positive reinforcement and using food to do counter-conditioning & desensitisation with your dog. You’re strengthening your bond, teaching your dog in a way they want to learn and are even excited to learn, and changing how your dog feels about certain situations in a positive way. Wear the “snack feeder” badge of honour... it’s better than trying to be the long debunked and outdated concept of “pack leader” <U+0001F60F> .  Also, if anyone tries to tell you force-free training makes dogs fat, check out #forcefreeandfit. Hehe I think I’m fit enough to belong in there! <U+0001F4AA> I also belong in the new hashtag: #forcefreeandhandsome <U+0001F923> .  #sonya6000 #dogsofsingapore #forcefreetraining #forcefree #dog #dogs #singaporedogs #spcasingapore #adoptdontshop #mongrel #positivereinforcement #mongrelsofinstagram #dogstagram #muttsofinstagram #mutt #singapawrean #singaporespecial #rescuedog #rescuedogsofinstagram #shelterdog #shelterdogsofinstagram  #dogsofliverpool #dogsofengland #dogsofbritain #liverpooldogs #liverpoolpets

Reacted to a little shihtzu this morning. <U+0001F62A> It had growled at me the first time when I had just come out of the house and I didn’t react then. But on the way back from our walk, we ran into the same dog and this time we both reacted. <U+0001F62A> Human thinks it could also be the leash tension she accidentally put on me, or also trigger stacking.  The important thing is that it’s NOT any dog’s fault when dogs react! So there is absolutely no reason to punish your dog for expressing its fear and stress. That only makes things worse. Y’all Humans got to figure it out and learn how to help your dog, not simply force, flood, or punish.  So Human is back to doing more counter-conditioning and desensitisation with me, starting at a further distance again (swipe to see video). I’ve been improving so much with other dogs, apart from this one mishap today, that Human usually treats me when I’m a bit closer to the other dog(s). But today we’re starting back at a further distance with freshly cooked salmon, something that’s super high value so I can make the positive associations with seeing other dogs again. Seeing other dogs play sometimes freaks me out too (especially if they’re loud!)... so doing this with going past 2 rough playing dogs is an added bonus. <U+0001F601>  #sonya6000 #dogsofsingapore #forcefreetraining #forcefree #dog #dogs #singaporedogs #spcasingapore #adoptdontshop #mongrel #positivereinforcement #mongrelsofinstagram #dogstagram #muttsofinstagram #mutt #singapawrean #singaporespecial #rescuedog #rescuedogsofinstagram #shelterdog #shelterdogsofinstagram  #dogsofliverpool #dogsofengland #dogsofbritain #liverpooldogs #liverpoolpets #reactivedogsotw @reactivedogsotw #youdonthaveto

Meet this handsome rescue, Dave! “I met Dave in Dec 2016 when I was a volunteer dog walker at @spcasingapore. I bonded with him and trained with him as I became a volunteer dog mentor there. He was found in a car accident when he was 2 and had been at the shelter for 7 years. It’s hard to understand why looking at how handsome he is and how well-behaved he is. Perhaps it was because he’s older, or perhaps because he took a long time to warm up to people. But I found him soulful and thoughtful and just loved him. One month before I was leaving for the UK, I decided that I had to take him with me or I’d be constantly worrying and thinking about him. It was a short amount of time, but I made it happen. Put in a lot of effort in crate training him for the flight, and quite a bit of my savings... but it was all worth it! I’m currently doing a dogtraining course and I wouldn’t be able to get through it without him. He’s the perfect training partner and companion and it’s just been so easy having him around. It still amazes me how well and how quickly he adapted from shelter life in sunny Singapore to home life in chilly England. Maybe he knew that at least he finally gets to sleep on a comfortable bed at night.” <U+0001F49C>Give Dave some love<U+0001F49C> @dave_the_d0gg0<U+0001F49C> <U+0001F436> #singaporespecial #singaporerescue #singaporerescuedogs #spcasingapore #singaporedog #rescueddogs #rescuedog #rescuedogs #rescuepup #supportrescue #rescuepuppy #rescuedoggy #rescuedoggies #adoptdontshop #adoptdonotshop #rescuedogsrule #rescueismyfavouritebreed #amazingrescuestories #dogsofinstagram #rescueddogsforever

I’m so happy to graduate from the Victoria Stilwell Academy yesterday with a distinction and am now a VSA-CDT! While having this certification is very positively reinforcing and I’ve learnt so much through doing it, I will keep learning and keep doing better so that I can properly uphold the values this title stands for as well as help dogs and humans effectively and humanely. The Bucket Game by Chirag Patel is a good way to provide dogs with choice and the ability to consent. This is important especially for shelter dogs like Spotty @theawesome_pup here who don’t get to have many choices. With The Bucket Game, Spotty will not just learn to accept handling, but also be able to control when a procedure that involves handling (e.g. medical/grooming activities) starts and stops, rather than be pinned down by force or sedated. Having control and choice is such a strong reinforcer and reduces stress. <U+0001F4AA>  We are currently on the first step of teaching Spotty to look at the bucket, before adding any handling. Also gave Spotty a new @kongcompany toy to end the session with some fun! <U+0001F973> .  Spotty is up for adoption at @spcasingapore! I met Cinnamon when I began volunteering @spcasingapore in the middle of 2019. Then, he already had his beautiful snow-white muzzle, and the hairs around his eyes were speckled with white too. He’d grown up in the shelter, spending 8 years there. I wonder what many things he must have seen in his 8 years, which would have included the move of the shelter from Mt Vernon to Sungei Tengah in 2016.  I looked forward to seeing Cinnamon each week I went down - it’s not hard to see why, he has such a gorgeous smile! He loves his snuffle mats - many of the shelter dogs do - and it provided him with the opportunity to engage his nose. He enjoyed the occasional roll in the grass, or on a particular drain cover outside SPCA - must have been some funky smell he just had to cover himself in <U+0001F602>  But being in the shelter was stressful for Cinnamon too, who has such a sensitive soul. He was wary of things or people looming over him, there was the daily cacophony of sounds the dogs faced, the many strange people who passed through the shelter.  Well, Cinn’s 8 long years in the shelter concluded today. He went once more on a road trip - but this time to his very own loving home. So many people came to bid him farewell, and he relished the attention.  To my heart boy, Cinn Cinn: I hope you have many, many more wonderful, healthy years with your new family. May they be spent doing all the things you love - snuffling, rolling in funky smells, greeting your favourite humans... You deserve it, and so does every other shelter dog out there!

How do you tell if a dog wants to make contact? <U+0001F914>  In this video, I’m checking for consent from the dog before I touch him.  Truffles is a 10-year-old male poodle who was surrendered to the SPCA yesterday. As he had growled during the intake process just a few minutes before this video was taken, I was extra careful while approaching him.  I let him set the pace of interaction, waiting till he indicated he was ok to be touched.  In this case, he leaned towards my hand. Dogs can also indicate consent by licking your hand. I stop stroking him periodically to check if he was till comfortable.  When he heard some noises, he turned towards the sound and I stopped stroking him. I stopped to give him space and time to check out his environment. Just imagine if you were trying to figure out a difficult math problem and someone comes up to give you a massage or tries to talk to you. <U+0001F623>  But as you can see, after he was done checking out whatever that noise was, he was quite happy with human contact again. The huge payoff is when he moves closer to me. <U+0001F970><U+0001F970> **I’m currently fostering Truffles as we try and get some of his health issues sorted. So stay tuned for updates about this boy! He’d be up for adoption soon** #puppylove_sg #petsbehavingwell #positivereinforcement #singaporedogs #positivedogtraining #dogsofinstagram #sgdog  #spcasingapore #adoptme #fosteringsaveslives #fearfreeshelters

Adopting a senior dog is often a hard decision to make. "How long more can the dog live for?" "Soon will have health complications right?" "Wa so old already" It's so common to hear comments like this when people walk pass senior dogs. True, they may not be as bubbly, silly or active as they once were, and they probably have less time left with you. But when it comes to adopting a dog, it is very important to find the right fit. Older dogs are usually calmer, more independent, and does better when left alone for long hours (for 9am-6pm working adults). <U+0001F60A> So, without further ado, meet 11 years old Billa!! Don't let his age scare you, he is absolutely young at heart! He does well with car rides, walks really great on leash, and is still a curious little explorer. He is grass trained, hence he needs to be walked at least twice a day. Also, Billa is HDB approved!! <U+0001F389>  Billa does have some skin issues, but on a bright side, that gives him his cute panda eyes <U+0001F602>  #adoptdontshop #adoptadog #spcasingapore #adopt #singaporespecial #sgdogs #sgspecial

HELPER OF THE DAY: BILLA  What was supposed to be another usual 3km walk for Billa soon became a rescue mission as we passed by 2 pigeons lying motionless. DON’T MAKE PETS WEAR MASKS (COVID-19 ADVISORY) ~ reposted from @spcasingapore . As we battle the COVID-19 outbreak, concerned pet owners might be tempted to make their pets wear masks. Our vets strongly advise against doing so as this is unnecessary and comes with risks. On top of possibly causing significant discomfort, obscuring an animal’s mouth with a mask will hinder the animal from dispelling heat and could cause a serious heat injury. <U+0001F637> . According to the World Health Organisation (WHO), there is no evidence that pets such as dogs and cats can be infected by the virus. . Nonetheless, we should practice good hygiene while monitoring the situation closely. Keep your pets healthy by ensuring they are up to date on their vaccinations and other preventives, are on a nutritious diet and are brought to the vet for regular health check-ups. . #keepourpetssafe #keepourpetshealthy #spcasingapore #covid19 #covid19sg #covid19singapore #coronavirus #coronavírussg #coronavirussingapore #sgdogs #sgdog #sgcats #sgcat #sgpets #sgpet #dogsofinstagramsg #catsofinstagramsg #singaporedogs #singaporecats #petsmagazinesg #dogsofinstasg #catsofinstasg #dogsofsingapore #catsofsingapore #singaporepets #clubpetsmag #sgpetstagram #singapawrean #sgfurkids #thewoofagency

Puppies galore at the SPCA today! Volunteers from Aesop came down to the shelter and spent time with the little ones.  Such social interactions are invaluable for the puppies as they get to meet many different types of people in a safe and controlled manner. This is vitally important as the window of socialisation starts to close at about 16 weeks. After which, a puppy’s ability to accept new experiences is less elastic. This means new experiences has a higher chance to be met with a fearful response.  Thank you Aesop for helping to give these pups a helping hand!  #puppylove_sg #petsbehavingwell #positivereinforcement #singaporedogs #positivedogtraining #dogsofinstagram #sgdog  #corporatevolunteering #puppysocialization #aesop #spcasingapore  #adoptdontshop

The Bucket Game (by @chiragpatel.co ) helps us check for consent from our dogs whenever we have to handle and do tactile procedures with them. When the dog looks at the bucket, it means “yes continue”, when they look away from the bucket, it means “stop”. When a dog is allowed to have a choice in what happens to them, they are more empowered and will be more likely to say yes. This means we don’t have to force our dogs into being handled when they don’t want to or in ways that they don’t want to be handled. Instead, we can teach our dogs that they have a say in the handling, and if they consent, they most certainly get rewarded for it!  Notes: - Use a bucket/container that you will ONLY use for this purpose - Put food that your dog likes in the bucket and reward with the food from the bucket (this also helps with impulse control) - Remember to occasionally toggle back easier steps so as to not make things harder and harder for the dog.  #cooperativecare #consentfordogs #thebucketgame #dogtraining #dogsofsingapore #forcefreetraining #forcefree #dog #dogs #singaporedogs #spcasingapore #adoptdontshop #mongrel #positivereinforcement #mongrelsofinstagram #dogstagram #muttsofinstagram #mutt #singapawrean #singaporespecial #rescuedog #rescuedogsofinstagram #shelterdog #shelterdogsofinstagram  #dogsofliverpool #dogsofengland #dogsofbritain #liverpooldogs #liverpoolpets

Get the jump on plaque, one tooth at a time!  Roger, a 2-year-old Singapore Special adopted from SPCA, gets comfortable with having his teeth brushed. The session is kept short and fun. He gets a treat after every tooth! For some dogs, it might not even be possible to brush 1 tooth at first. In that case, just touch the brush to the tooth and treat.  Good dental hygiene helps keep periodontal disease and the dreaded doggie breath at bay. Infections in the mouth can lead to issues with your dog’s vital organs eg heart, kidney, liver. So start polishing your pooch’s pearly whites today!  #puppylove_sg #petsbehavingwell #positivereinforcement #singaporedogs #positivedogtraining #dogsofinstagram #sgdog  #spcasingapore

The Taxman Cometh! And in this case we roll out the welcome mat! <U+0001F604>  The lovely volunteers from IRAS (Inland Revenue Authority of Singapore) spent the morning with our shelter dogs and puppies. They took Beary the chow mix and Masson, a very energetic adolescent on a long walk. <U+0001F415> <U+0001F429><U+0001F3C3><U+0001F3FB><U+200D><U+2642><U+FE0F><U+0001F3C3><U+0001F3FB><U+200D><U+2640><U+FE0F> The volunteers also spent time with the little puppies in the shelter. <U+0001F436> <U+0001F38A>Thank you IRAS!<U+0001F38A> PS - You might be wondering if it’s the same Beary as in my earlier posts. Yes it’s the same poor misunderstood Beary <U+0001F43B> that myself and a team of trainers have been working on.  Beary is actually a pretty easygoing dog and apart from the grooming aspect, he’s quite low maintenance. He prefers to do his business on grass and will not go indoors if he can help it.  Beary is still waiting for his forever home. If you are looking for a chill companion, do get in touch with the SPCA or myself! . #puppylove_sg #spcasingapore #positivereinforcementtraining #corporatevolunteering #chowchow #singaporechow #singaporechowchows #singaporespecial #dogsofinstagram #inlandrevenueauthorityofsingapore

Until the right hoomen came and I put it to test!! It worked!! This hoomen override my pending queue and the next thing I knew, I have a HOME, a fureva home... Hoomen took me to the doctor and the doctor said I could have been born sometime in Feb 7. Fast forward 5years later, here I am, anticipating my birthday with a family of my own!!! Love ... Love ...
